                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d65">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4 General Committee (Arms)/357:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        American Delegate</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-06-29T12:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 29, 1935—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>497. Wilson’s telegram No. 295, June 28, 3 p.m. from London. I concur in your
                    opinion that consideration of the British suggestion may well be deferred until
                    after your return to Geneva.</p>
                <p>In the meantime without desiring to commit ourselves definitely, you are
                    informed, for your guidance, that we feel that it would be unwise for us to
                    entertain any suggestions for compromise on the essential points which Stanhope
                    and Stevenson have discussed with you until there is definite reason to believe
                    that concessions on our part would result in a general acceptance of the
                    Convention in the immediate future.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
